==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|lof|lang=fro}}. ''Collins English Dictionary'' states that this word is ultimately derived from {{etyl|dum|en}} {{term|loef|lang=dum}}.<ref>{{R:Dictionary.com}}</ref> Ellert Ekwall's ''Shakspere's Vocabulary: its etymological elements'' (1903) related this verb and {{term|loof|lang=en}} instead to the East Frisian<!--caution: has no code! frs is ambiguous, see BP discussion--> verb ''lofen'', ''lufen'', which would make it cognate to the French term {{term|lover|lang=fr}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/lʌf/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ʌf|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} The [[vertical]] [[edge]] of a [[sail]] that is closest to the direction of the [[wind]].
#: ''By easing the [[halyard]], the '''luff''' of the sail was made to sag to [[leeward]].''
# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} The act of sailing a ship close to the wind.
# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} The roundest part of a ship's bow.
# {{context|nautical|lang=en}} The forward or weather leech of a sail, especially of the jib, spanker, and other fore-and-aft sails.

